One Fish/One Namibia, the first National Data Modelling for Fisheries Management and Implementation Project that is now reaching completion. In the preceding 5 years the most significant event was the first RBF workshop in 2011, where we collected feedback from scientists, politicians, NGO’s and CBO’s from the fisheries, agriculture, conservation areas, eco-tourism, and other sectors (including petroleum and mining), on what the best tools were to use in order to build a sustainable fisheries management system.
Come to the Ocean of the Future Karien Basson, Head of Sustainable Fisheries – WWF International
If we look at the state of our oceans today, viewing this not as specialists in marine science but as everyday coastal communities, we can easily feel despair. Overfishing and unequal access are having a significant negative impact on coastal communities living in poverty, despite increasing volumes of fish illegally land from developing countries.
But, six countries – the Philippines, Indonesia, Vanuatu, Thailand, Namibia and Papua New Guinea to date –have progressed from this costal despair to a brighter, more sustainable future. They seized the opportunity to protect the ocean and empower local communities through an innovative financing window within the World Bank’s Global Environmental Facility (GEF), the Resource Management and Environment Loan (REM).
Namibia: iSimangaliso Marine World Fisheries welcomes the opportunity to once again be part of RBF. The theme of this year’s conference is encouraging and pertinent for Namibia
